In response to the message sent  Fri, 15 Aug 86 13:17:59 EDT from philipp@athena.mit.edu

When the present top-levels of the domain system were set up, a
top-level domain was reserved for each country, in the form of the ISO
standard 2 letter country code.  (Of course the first country that
wanted its domain also wanted a different code, but that's another
story.)  Few countries have been set up as yet, for example the
top-level domains UK, IL, AU exist.  Canada is welcome to have its
top-level domain.

To start one up, it must be delegated by the root of the domain tree,
which is managed by the NIC.  Technically its easy to do, once they
believe you are reasonably entitled to run the Canada domain.  There are
some technical requirements you must meet, such as identifying redundant
servers for the domain.  Note that these servers can be anywhere;
although most delegated domains use local servers, Canada could decide
to use two machines in Australia if it wanted to.  While Australia
probably isn't a good choice, you might want to find a well-connected
(network wise) friend south of the border to redundantly serve the
Canada domain while you build up your connectivity.

paul
